'''Route 98''' is a southwest-northeast numbered highway in central Massachusetts. The highway is a continuation of [[Rhode Island Route 98]] in [[Uxbridge, Massachusetts|Uxbridge]].

==Route description==
The route passes through Aldrich Village, crossing the [[Rhode Island Route 7|Douglas Pike]] and passing a number of buildings on the [[National Historic Register]]. <ref name = "walking">{{cite web |title= "Walking tours - Uxbridge"|publisher= Blackstone Daily |url= http://www.blackstonedaily.com/Outdoors&Nature/WTuxbridge|accessdate=2007-12-08}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>.  One of the historic buildings is the [[Friends Meetinghouse (Uxbridge, Massachusetts)|Friends Meetinghouse]] which is at the northern terminus of Route 98. Abolitionist [[Abby Kelley Foster]] was a member here. The [[Southern New England Trunkline Trail]] crosses Route 98 a short distance south of the Quaker Meeting house and the junction with Route 146A. 
 

Route 98 passes under [[Massachusetts Route 146|Route 146]] without junction shortly before its northern end at [[Massachusetts Route 146A|Route 146A]], between Exits 1 and 2 of Route 146.  The entire route in Massachusetts takes only 3.87 miles (6.23 km).

==Junction list==
The entire highway is in [[Uxbridge, Massachusetts|Uxbridge]], [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester County]]
